        <svcproc svcproctype="afcrepair" graphiccount="1">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the four (4) upper mounting bolts which correspond to the slots in the mounting
                    casting and the two (2) lower refrigerant compressor mounting bolts which correspond to the slots in
                    the adjustment bracket.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Back off the tension on the compressor adjusting bolt until the compressor is loose and
                    the belt is slack. Remove the belt and discard.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>92/9400's and Vision 98 vehicles built between September 19, 1996 and October 23, 1996, and
                        9800's built between September 26, 1996 and November 11, 1996 will not require the use of the
                        studs, washers, and nuts, but will require all other kit components. The machined width of the
                        adjustment slots in these mounting castings has been reduced. Do not attempt to install the
                        studs on vehicles built between these two date windows or compressor damage may occur.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the two (2) upper compressor mounting bolts which correspond to the two
                    adjustment slots closest to the front of the vehicle (refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9690701">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9690701" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g9690701" filename="../afcfigures/g9690701.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use Loctite 272 on the short thread portion of the stud, install the short thread end of
                    the two (2) studs into the compressor mounting holes and tighten finger tight plus 1/4 turn. Install
                    the two (2) flat washers and two (2) nuts, and finger tighten all compressor mounting bolts.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen and unscrew the lower front casting mounting bolt approximately 1/4 inch.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the casting upper mounting bolt.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the new idler pulley bracket by sliding the slotted hole in the bracket behind
                    the lower mounting bolt head and by re-installing the upper mounting bolt through the unslotted
                    hole. Tighten both bolts to 30 to 38 ft-lbs. (40 to 51 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the dust shield on the snap ring side of the pulley and push the torx bolt through
                    the center of the pulley. Install this assembly to the threaded boss on the idler bracket. Use a
                    T-50 torx socket to tighten the idler pulley bolt to 25 to 35 ft-lbs. (33 to 47 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Poly-V belt tension cannot be estimated with thumb deflection, cricket style gauges, torque
                        resistance, or by any other method. A quality dial indicating tension gauge that has been
                        designed and calibrated for use with Poly-V belts must be used (tension gauge part number ZTOEM
                        1294).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Belt tension adjustments made without the use of a dial indicating tension gauge have been
                        rechecked and found to be between 85 and 400 pounds after the belt tensioning procedure is
                        completed. For additional belt tensioning information, refer to TSI-96-12-23.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the new belt installed, turn the adjustment bolt until all excess slack is taken
                    up. The belt should be loose with no slack. DO NOT APPLY ANY ADDITIONAL TENSION YET.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten all six compressor mounting bolts to 24 ft-lbs. and then back each one off 1/2
                    turn only.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mount your belt tension gauge (ZTOEM 1294) to the top of the belt and turn the
                    adjustment bolt slowly until you reach 180 lbs. of belt tension. You will notice that it now takes a
                    little more effort to turn the adjustment bolt.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the correct tension is reached, re-tighten all six compressor mounting bolts to 24
                    ft-lbs. and tighten the jam nut on the adjustment bolt.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Following 2-3 minutes of engine operation at high idle with the A/C on, recheck the belt
                    tension with the belt tension gauge. Tension should be no less than 120 lbs.
                </para>
            </step1>
